This is a known pain point. In .NET 10, Android's `adjustResize` (which `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` mapped to) is fully deprecated. Here's the modern approach:

## 1. Set `adjustResize` directly in the manifest

It still *works* on most devices even though deprecated. In `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`, add to your `<activity>`:

```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize">
```

## 2. If that's not enough, use the WindowInsets API

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`, opt into edge-to-edge inset handling:

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Let the app draw behind the keyboard area
        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window!, false);

        // React to keyboard (IME) insets
        var rootView = FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(rootView, new InsetsListener());
    }

    private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var sysInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars());
            var bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, sysInsets.Bottom);

            v.SetPadding(sysInsets.Left, sysInsets.Top, sysInsets.Right, bottom);
            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

## 3. Disable `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (it can conflict)

In `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
#if ANDROID
Microsoft.Maui.Platform.KeyboardAutoManagerScroll.Disconnect();
#endif
```

## 4. XAML layout tip

Use a `Grid` so the input bar naturally sits at the bottom and the message list shrinks when padding changes:

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" />
    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

**iOS** handles this automatically with `adjustResize`-like behavior by default, but if needed you can listen for `UIKeyboard.WillShowNotification` and adjust bottom padding similarly in `Platforms/iOS/`.

**TL;DR:** Option 2 (WindowInsets) is the future-proof solution. Option 1 (manifest flag) is the quick fix that still works today.
